about my helmet?

82
00:12:28,480 --> 00:12:31,484
You look like a massive nerd,
even around other scientists.

83
00:12:32,283 --> 00:12:33,421
Can I just ask?

84
00:12:33,519 --> 00:12:35,759
Were you wearing the helmet
while she dumped you?

85
00:12:35,855 --> 00:12:38,392
See, it protects
my very important brain,
Harper.

86
00:12:39,057 --> 00:12:40,900
Go prep the samples.

87
00:12:42,094 --> 00:12:45,234
Hey. I found you.
Betty, hey.

88
00:12:48,834 --> 00:12:51,904
I hate them.
Wait, I just got here.
Who do we hate?

89
00:12:51,971 --> 00:12:54,849
The review board.
We have to make
a presentation on Tuesday.

90
00:12:55,073 --> 00:12:56,279
(GROANING)

91
00:12:56,375 --> 00:12:58,047
And you're gonna
make it with me.

92
00:12:59,311 --> 00:13:02,655
You think I should?
Yeah, you're great
with that stuff.

93
00:13:03,048 --> 00:13:05,356
You start talking about
microbes and nanomeds,

94
00:13:05,417 --> 00:13:07,988
you sound almost passionate.

95
00:13:11,190 --> 00:13:14,067
I'm sorry. That was rude.

96
00:13:14,192 --> 00:13:16,195
Look, nobody expects
this to be easy,

97
00:13:16,662 --> 00:13:20,404
us working together
after being so close.

98
00:13:21,299 --> 00:13:22,607
We were close?

99
00:13:22,701 --> 00:13:23,803
(SNORTS)

100
00:13:23,936 --> 00:13:26,005
Look, if I could be more

101
00:13:27,338 --> 00:13:30,547
whatever, you know.
I'm just...

102
00:13:30,975 --> 00:13:33,922
Don't. It's not
your fault, really.

103
00:13:34,846 --> 00:13:37,485
You're just a byproduct
of my inexplicable obsession

104
00:13:37,549 --> 00:13:39,359
with emotionally distant men.

105
00:13:39,951 --> 00:13:41,522
I'll get over us.

106
00:13:42,955 --> 00:13:43,990
Good for you.

107
00:13:44,056 --> 00:13:46,536
Anyway, I'm just really
stressed about this review.

108
00:13:46,826 --> 00:13:48,429
If we don't get
impressive results today,

109
00:13:48,494 --> 00:13:50,974
we're gonna have a really
hard sell come Tuesday.

110
00:13:52,865 --> 00:13:54,900
Well, then,
let's go be impressive.

111
00:14:39,311 --> 00:14:40,517
Harper?

112
00:14:40,578 --> 00:14:43,524
Ready when you are.
Let's hit it.

113
00:14:48,419 --> 00:14:49,864
Are we passing inspection?

114
00:14:50,255 --> 00:14:54,431
Safeties all going green.
Countdown's started.

115
00:14:58,264 --> 00:14:59,868
Nanomeds released.

116
00:15:01,799 --> 00:15:03,573
Four seconds.

117
00:15:07,038 --> 00:15:09,849
Okay, nanomeds
fully dispersed.

118
00:15:11,176 --> 00:15:14,850
Okay, let's hit Freddie
with the gamma radiation.

119
00:15:28,293 --> 00:15:29,932
Gamma exposure.

120
00:15:31,730 --> 00:15:33,299
Nanomeds now active.

121
00:15:38,003 --> 00:15:40,642
HARPER: Nanomeds
replicating cells on border.

122
00:15:41,105 --> 00:15:42,174
It's working.

123
00:15:46,312 --> 00:15:50,157
HARPER: Cell copy
to disassemble ratio
holding within 1 %.

124
00:15:57,556 --> 00:16:00,092
Imbalanced nanomed activity.

125
00:16:13,038 --> 00:16:14,572
You wanna go to
the review board on Monday

126
00:16:14,639 --> 00:16:17,779
and tell them we've developed
a brand-new method
for exploding frogs?

127
00:16:17,842 --> 00:16:20,788
Yeah, I think maybe
there's a market for it.

128
00:16:21,212 --> 00:16:22,817
I mean, what if
there's a plague?

129
00:16:24,283 --> 00:16:26,125
What have you had, Betty,
like, one beer?

130
00:16:26,184 --> 00:16:31,759
I'm just... I'm just saying,
you know, frogs start falling
from the sky,

131
00:16:32,390 --> 00:16:34,062
who do they come to?

132
00:16:34,826 --> 00:16:38,466
We'd be world-renowned.
Make any parent proud.

133
00:16:39,965 --> 00:16:41,534
I bet they would be.

134
00:16:42,301 --> 00:16:44,677
They actually did want me
to be a scientist.

135
00:16:46,171 --> 00:16:48,014
I mean, your birth parents.

136
00:16:50,042 --> 00:16:51,451
Guess we'll never know.

137
00:16:51,710 --> 00:16:52,880
(SIGHS)

138
00:16:54,913 --> 00:16:57,859
I don't understand
why you don't want to
find out about them.

139
00:16:57,915 --> 00:17:01,385
They're dead.
They died before I could
remember anything.

140
00:17:01,754 --> 00:17:03,857
Why do you always
come back to this?

141
00:17:04,722 --> 00:17:05,997
Don't know.

142
00:17:06,625 --> 00:17:09,627
I guess I figure
there's more to you
than you like to show.

143
00:17:11,195 --> 00:17:13,038
I guess there
couldn't be any less.

144
00:17:14,532 --> 00:17:17,376
Right. So now we come
full circle back to that.

145
00:17:17,435 --> 00:17:19,107
Nice work, Betty.

146
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:29,548
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

147
00:17:33,051 --> 00:17:34,258
Betty.

148
00:17:36,055 --> 00:17:37,534
Glenn.
Hey.

149
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:40,332
Hi.
Hi.

150
00:17:43,095 --> 00:17:44,868
What happened to your uniform?

151
00:17:45,463 --> 00:17:47,603
Oh, I switched over.

152
00:17:47,833 --> 00:17:49,743
I'm still working
with your father, but...

153
00:17:49,968 --> 00:17:51,810
Well, you know,
the military's
subcontracting out

154
00:17:51,869 --> 00:17:53,747
all the most
interesting work, and...

155
00:17:55,473 --> 00:17:57,145
Can't argue with the paycheck.

156
00:17:58,076 --> 00:18:00,352
I basically run all the labs
on the base now.

157
00:18:03,882 --> 00:18:05,361
Hey, you're...

158
00:18:06,518 --> 00:18:08,019
You're looking good.

159
00:18:14,425 --> 00:18:15,961
You're the genetics expert.

160
00:18:27,905 --> 00:18:30,009
Ah, the good old college days.

161
00:18:32,277 --> 00:18:34,017
So, how's business?

162
00:18:35,780 --> 00:18:37,055
What do you want?

163
00:18:38,851 --> 00:18:39,885
(CLEARS THROAT)

164
00:18:39,951 --> 00:18:41,726
All right,
I'll cut to the chase.

165
00:18:42,753 --> 00:18:45,529
I've been hearing
interesting things about
what you guys are doing here.

166
00:18:45,590 --> 00:18:49,038
Your little molecular
machines have some
incredible implications.

167
00:18:49,827 --> 00:18:52,035
How would you like
to come work for Atheon?

168
00:18:52,096 --> 00:18:54,873
Get paid 1 0 times as much
as you earn now

169
00:18:55,366 --> 00:18:57,471
and own a piece
of the patents.

170
00:19:00,038 --> 00:19:04,247
You just have to say the word.
Two words, the door.

171
00:19:20,826 --> 00:19:21,826
(DOOR CLOSING)

172
00:19:24,563 --> 00:19:26,940
General?
Come in.

173
00:19:28,733 --> 00:19:30,804
Talbot wanted you
to see this, sir.

174
00:19:31,403 --> 00:19:35,406
It's about a lab Atheon
is targeting for acquisition
and removal to Desert Base.

175
00:19:36,307 --> 00:19:38,447
Why isn't it going
through NSC?

176
00:19:40,913 --> 00:19:43,858
It concerns
your daughter, sir.

177
00:19:52,156 --> 00:19:53,931
Hi. Sorry.

178
00:19:56,595 --> 00:20:00,166
Hey, what happened to Benny?
Is he not working
the night shift anymore?

179
00:20:00,365 --> 00:20:03,367
Benny's dead.
I'm the new guy.

180
00:20:05,103 --> 00:20:06,172
Oh.

181
00:20:08,272 --> 00:20:10,012
Good to meet you.
Same.

182
00:20:34,465 --> 00:20:35,807
(CLICKS)

183
00:20:36,101 --> 00:20:38,911
Let's try another.
No, stay here.

184
00:20:39,704 --> 00:20:42,947
I look tired anyway.
Yeah, but you look great.

185
00:20:46,677 --> 00:20:48,054
What's the matter?

186
00:20:48,480 --> 00:20:49,822
(CHUCKLES)

187
00:20:50,115 --> 00:20:54,586
It's these dreams, Doctor.
I keep having them
and they're terrible.

188
00:20:56,153 --> 00:20:57,927
Tell me about your dream.

189
00:21:01,159 --> 00:21:02,865
Well, it starts...

190
00:21:03,729 --> 00:21:06,799
It starts with a memory.
I think it's my first memory.

191
00:21:06,865 --> 00:21:09,742
It's this image I have

192
00:21:10,234 --> 00:21:12,738
from when I was maybe
two years old.

193
00:21:44,536 --> 00:21:46,480
Do you think
it's just a dream?

194
00:21:47,005 --> 00:21:48,744
No, I think it's something
that happened

195
00:21:48,807 --> 00:21:52,048
when I was living
at a desert base
with my father.

196
00:21:53,545 --> 00:21:56,752
BETTY: Anyhow,
the dream goes on

197
00:21:56,882 --> 00:21:59,657
and suddenly l'm alone.

198
00:22:35,619 --> 00:22:38,964
That's terrible.
You know I'd never hurt you.

199
00:22:53,739 --> 00:22:55,650
(DOG WHIMPERING)

200
00:22:57,108 --> 00:22:58,519
(DOOR CLOSING)

201
00:23:16,027 --> 00:23:17,300
Hey, there.

202
00:23:19,196 --> 00:23:21,006
What's your name, darling?

203
00:23:22,334 --> 00:23:23,505
What's your name?

204
00:23:23,567 --> 00:23:24,704
(SNARLING)

205
00:23:25,103 --> 00:23:27,980
Okay. It's okay.

206
00:23:35,713 --> 00:23:37,625
(TYPING)

207
00:23:42,953 --> 00:23:44,728
(KEYS JANGLING)

208
00:24:39,544 --> 00:24:41,078
(TYPING)

209
00:25:19,750 --> 00:25:22,628
DAVlD: l gotta
talk to you, Edith.
EDITH: Bruce, stay here.

210
00:25:23,320 --> 00:25:24,628
(GASPING)

211
00:25:25,490 --> 00:25:27,162
(PANTING)

212
00:25:28,359 --> 00:25:29,894
(DOG WHIMPERING)

213
00:26:39,763 --> 00:26:41,402
(FROG CROAKING)

214
00:26:43,602 --> 00:26:47,777
C, T, G, A,

215
00:26:48,772 --> 00:26:50,251
G.

216
00:26:52,042 --> 00:26:53,714
Bruce.

217
00:27:00,417 --> 00:27:02,056
My Bruce.

218
00:27:11,730 --> 00:27:14,267
Morning. Glenn dropped by.

219
00:27:14,833 --> 00:27:17,643
What's he doing here?
You know, Dr. Krenzler,

220
00:27:18,303 --> 00:27:21,113
you and I have never had
the chance to get to know
each other properly.

221
00:27:21,172 --> 00:27:24,675
Well, that's because I don't
want to get to know you,
properly or improperly.

222
00:27:24,742 --> 00:27:25,949
(BEEPING)

223
00:27:26,611 --> 00:27:28,055
So leave.

224
00:27:29,013 --> 00:27:30,492
Hey, no worries.

225
00:27:39,758 --> 00:27:41,430
Let me give you
a little heads up.

226
00:27:42,460 --> 00:27:46,874
There is a hair's breadth
between friendly offer
and hostile takeover.

227
00:27:47,365 --> 00:27:51,243
I've done my homework.
The work you're doing
here is dynamite.

228
00:27:51,435 --> 00:27:54,108
Think, GIs embedded
with technology

229
00:27:54,172 --> 00:27:56,948
that makes them instantly
repairable on the battlefield

230
00:27:57,208 --> 00:27:59,050
in our sole possession.

231
00:27:59,778 --> 00:28:03,191
That's a hell of a business.
Well, it's not
what we're doing here.

232
00:28:03,548 --> 00:28:05,993
We're doing the basic science
for everyone.

233
00:28:08,853 --> 00:28:11,855
You know, someday
I'm gonna write a book
and I'm gonna call it,

234
00:28:11,923 --> 00:28:16,064
When Stupid ldeals Happen
to Smart Penniless Scientists.

235
00:28:17,327 --> 00:28:19,830
In the meantime, Bruce,
you will be hearing from me.

236
00:28:42,987 --> 00:28:46,433
About Glenn, I...
There's nothing to talk about.

237
00:28:49,961 --> 00:28:51,132
Okay.

238
00:28:51,895 --> 00:28:53,965
I just wanted to say,
don't worry about him.

239
00:28:54,298 --> 00:28:55,742
I'll handle it.

240
00:28:58,737 --> 00:29:00,215
How?

241
00:29:01,306 --> 00:29:05,913
I'm gonna call my father,
ask him to exert
some pressure.

242
00:29:06,644 --> 00:29:09,453
Last I heard,
you and your father
weren't speaking.

243
00:29:11,715 --> 00:29:13,286
Well,

244
00:29:13,951 --> 00:29:16,659
I guess now I have something
to talk with him about.

245
00:29:17,422 --> 00:29:19,834
HARPER: l think this circuit's
kind of fried. l don't know.

246
00:29:19,891 --> 00:29:22,029
Maybe you wanna
come take a look at it.

247
00:29:22,227 --> 00:29:23,830
Okay, l'll be right there.

248
00:29:32,237 --> 00:29:33,306
(CRACKLING)

249
00:29:33,371 --> 00:29:34,372
(GRUNTS)

250
00:29:34,873 --> 00:29:36,282
(HARPER GROANING)

